{"title_page": "Sports science", "text_new": "{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2010}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2018}}\n}}\n'''Sports Science''' (aka '''Sports Science & Medicine''') is a discipline that studies how the healthy human body works during exercise, and how sport and physical activity promote health and performance from cellular to whole body perspectives. The study of sports science traditionally incorporates areas of [[physiology]] ([[exercise physiology]]), [[psychology]] ([[sport psychology]]), [[anatomy]], [[biomechanics]], [[biochemistry]], and [[kinesiology|biokinetics]]. Sports scientists and performance consultants are growing in demand and employment numbers, with the ever-increasing focus within the sporting world on achieving the best results possible. Through the study of science and sport, researchers have developed a greater understanding on how the human body reacts to exercise, training, different environments and many other stimuli.\n\n== Origins of exercise physiology ==\n{{main|Exercise physiology}}\n{{More citations needed|section|date=January 2018}}\n\nSports science can trace its origins to ancient Greece. The noted ancient Greek physician [[Galen]] (131\u2013201) wrote 87 detailed essays about improving health (proper nutrition), aerobic fitness, and strengthening muscles.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berryman |first1=Jack |last2=Park |first2=Roberta |title=Sport and Exercise Science |date=1992 |publisher=University of Illinois Press |location=Urbana and Chicago |isbn=0-252-01896-6 |pages=14\u201319 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TVklQ4FX76wC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=Galen+sports+science&source=bl&ots=Gr-cBGAhIf&sig=ACfU3U21h4acP3nuRmzYfgCstuXfEFCx8Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwihr9DK2fffAhUPSN8KHWSqCgwQ6AEwDnoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=Galen%20sports%20science&f=false |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nNew ideas upon the working and functioning of the human body emerged during the Renaissance as anatomists and physicians challenged the previously known theories. These spread with the implementation of the printed word, the result of [[Johannes Gutenberg|Gutenberg]]'s printing press in the 15th century. Allied with this was a large increase in academia in general, universities were forming all around the world. Importantly these new scholars went beyond the simplistic notions of the early Greek physicians, and shed light upon the complexities of the circulatory, and digestive systems. Furthermore, by the middle of the 19th century, early medical schools (such as the [[Harvard Medical School]], formed 1782) began appearing in the United States, whose graduates went on to assume positions of importance in academia and allied medical research.\n\nMedical journal publications increased significantly in number during this period. In 1898, three articles on physical activity appeared in the first volume of the '' [[American Journal of Physiology]]''. Other articles and reviews subsequently appeared in prestigious journals. The German applied physiology publication, '' Internationale Zeitschrift fur Physiologie einschliesslich Arbeitphysiologie '' (1929\u20131940; now known as the [[:nl:European Journal of Applied Physiology|European Journal of Applied Physiology]] and Occupational Physiology), became a significant journal in the field of research.\n\nA number of key figures have made significant contributions to the study of sports science: \n* [[Austin Flint, 2nd|Austin Flint, Jr]]., (1836\u20131915) One of the first American pioneer physicians, studied physiological responses to exercise in his influential medical textbooks.<ref>{{cite book |last1=McArdle |first1=William |last2=Katch |first2=Frank |last3=Katch |first3=Victor |title=Essentials of Exercise Physiology |date=2006 |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=United States of America |isbn=0-7817-4991-3 |page=8 |edition=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L4aZIDbmV3oC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=austin+flint+jr+textbook&source=bl&ots=WnqYw7Jg0M&sig=ACfU3U2q1g_HI3hQf9BeuaZogU_Xczp10w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjn2q-h4fffAhUrU98KHcEoAPQQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=austin%20flint%20jr%20textbook&f=false |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Edward Hitchcock, Jr.]], (1828\u20131911) [[Amherst College]] Professor of Hygiene and Physical Education, devoted his academic career to the scientific study of physical exercise, training and the body. Coauthored 1860 text on exercise physiology.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sweet |first1=William |title=150 Years Ago: Amherst Established Nation\u2019s First College Health Program |url=https://www.amherst.edu/news/news_releases/2011/08/node/337711/ |website=amherst.edu |publisher=Amherst College |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* George Wells Fitz, M.D. (1860\u20131934) Created the first departmental major in Anatomy, Physiology, and Physical Training at Harvard University in 1891.<ref>{{cite book |last1=McArdle |first1=William |last2=Katch |first2=Frank |last3=Katch |first3=Victor |title=Essentials of Exercise Physiology |date=2006 |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=USA |isbn=0-7817-4991-3 |page=9 |edition=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L4aZIDbmV3oC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=austin+flint+jr+textbook&source=bl&ots=WnqYw7Jg0M&sig=ACfU3U2q1g_HI3hQf9BeuaZogU_Xczp10w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjn2q-h4fffAhUrU98KHcEoAPQQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=austin%20flint%20jr%20textbook&f=false |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[August Krogh]] (1874\u20131949) Won the 1920 Nobel prize in physiology for discovering the mechanism that controlled capillary blood flow in resting or active muscle.<ref>{{cite web|title=August Krogh Biographical |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1920/krogh/biographical/ |website=NobelPrize.org |publisher=The Nobel Prize Organization |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Per-Olof \u00c5strand]] (1922\u20132015) Professor at the Department of Physiology, [[Karolinska Institute]], Stockholm. Wrote a seminal paper which evaluated the physical working capacity of men and women aged 4\u201333 years.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Astrand |first1=Per-Olof |last2=Rodahl |first2=Kaare |last3=Dahl |first3=Hans |last4=Stromme |first4=Sigmund |title=The Textbook of Work Physiology |date=2003 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |location=USA |isbn=0-7360-0140-9 |pages=260\u2013288 |edition=4th |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=BC9SiAsUPqsC&oi=fnd&pg=PR5&dq=per+olof+astrand+exercise+physiology&ots=8X_O3Zpm0r&sig=EFetDz5pmsfOebJDuu3phsxlXXA#v=onepage&q=age&f=false |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Study of sports science ==\nHigher-education degrees in Sports Science or Human Physiology are also becoming increasingly popular with many universities now offering both undergraduate, postgraduate and distance learning degrees in the discipline. Opportunities for graduates in these fields include employment as a [[Physical Education|Physical Education teacher]], [[Dietician]] or [[Nutritionist]], Performance Analyst, Sports coach, Sports therapist, Fitness center manager, Sports administrator, Strength and Conditioning specialist or retail manager of a Sports store. Graduates may also be well-positioned to undertake further training to become an accredited Physiotherapist, Exercise Physiologist, Research Scientist and Sports Medical Doctor.\n\n== Academic journals in sports science ==\n* ''[[Journal of Applied Biomechanics]]''\n* ''[[International Journal of Computer Science in Sport]]''\n* ''[[Journal of Strength & Conditioning Research]]''\n* ''[[Journal of Swimming Research]]''\n* ''[[Sports (journal)|Sports]]''\n* ''[[Medicine & Science in Sports & Exercise]]''\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kinesiology]]\n* [[Kinanthropometry]]\n* [[Sports biomechanics]]\n* [[Sports medicine]]\n* [[Computer science in sport]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bases.org.uk/newsite/home.asp British Association of Sport and Exercise Sciences]\n* [http://www.acsm.org American College of Sports Medicine]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090803130839/http://www.ecss.de/ European College of Sport Science]\n* [http://www.essa.org.au Exercise & Sports Science Australia]\n* [http://www.nsca.com/Home/ National Strength & Conditioning Association]\n\n{{Sport}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sports science| ]]\n[[Category:Applied sciences]]\n", "text_old": "{{multiple issues|\n{{More citations needed|date=December 2010}}\n{{More footnotes|date=January 2018}}\n}}\n'''Sports science''' (also '''sports and exercise science''', '''sports medicine''') is a discipline that studies how the healthy human body works during exercise, and how sport and physical activity promote health and performance from cellular to whole body perspectives. The study of sports science traditionally incorporates areas of [[physiology]] ([[exercise physiology]]), [[psychology]] ([[sport psychology]]), [[anatomy]], [[biomechanics]], [[biochemistry]], and [[kinesiology|biokinetics]]. Sports scientists and performance consultants are growing in demand and employment numbers, with the ever-increasing focus within the sporting world on achieving the best results possible. Through the study of science and sport, researchers have developed a greater understanding on how the human body reacts to exercise, training, different environments and many other stimuli.\n\n== Origins of exercise physiology ==\n{{main|Exercise physiology}}\n{{More citations needed|section|date=January 2018}}\n\nSports science can trace its origins to ancient Greece. The noted ancient Greek physician [[Galen]] (131\u2013201) wrote 87 detailed essays about improving health (proper nutrition), aerobic fitness, and strengthening muscles.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Berryman |first1=Jack |last2=Park |first2=Roberta |title=Sport and Exercise Science |date=1992 |publisher=University of Illinois Press |location=Urbana and Chicago |isbn=0-252-01896-6 |pages=14\u201319 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=TVklQ4FX76wC&pg=PA14&lpg=PA14&dq=Galen+sports+science&source=bl&ots=Gr-cBGAhIf&sig=ACfU3U21h4acP3nuRmzYfgCstuXfEFCx8Q&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwihr9DK2fffAhUPSN8KHWSqCgwQ6AEwDnoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=Galen%20sports%20science&f=false |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n\nNew ideas upon the working and functioning of the human body emerged during the Renaissance as anatomists and physicians challenged the previously known theories. These spread with the implementation of the printed word, the result of [[Johannes Gutenberg|Gutenberg]]'s printing press in the 15th century. Allied with this was a large increase in academia in general, universities were forming all around the world. Importantly these new scholars went beyond the simplistic notions of the early Greek physicians, and shed light upon the complexities of the circulatory, and digestive systems. Furthermore, by the middle of the 19th century, early medical schools (such as the [[Harvard Medical School]], formed 1782) began appearing in the United States, whose graduates went on to assume positions of importance in academia and allied medical research.\n\nMedical journal publications increased significantly in number during this period. In 1898, three articles on physical activity appeared in the first volume of the '' [[American Journal of Physiology]]''. Other articles and reviews subsequently appeared in prestigious journals. The German applied physiology publication, '' Internationale Zeitschrift fur Physiologie einschliesslich Arbeitphysiologie '' (1929\u20131940; now known as the [[:nl:European Journal of Applied Physiology|European Journal of Applied Physiology]] and Occupational Physiology), became a significant journal in the field of research.\n\nA number of key figures have made significant contributions to the study of sports science: \n* [[Austin Flint, 2nd|Austin Flint, Jr]]., (1836\u20131915) One of the first American pioneer physicians, studied physiological responses to exercise in his influential medical textbooks.<ref>{{cite book |last1=McArdle |first1=William |last2=Katch |first2=Frank |last3=Katch |first3=Victor |title=Essentials of Exercise Physiology |date=2006 |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=United States of America |isbn=0-7817-4991-3 |page=8 |edition=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L4aZIDbmV3oC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=austin+flint+jr+textbook&source=bl&ots=WnqYw7Jg0M&sig=ACfU3U2q1g_HI3hQf9BeuaZogU_Xczp10w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjn2q-h4fffAhUrU98KHcEoAPQQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=austin%20flint%20jr%20textbook&f=false |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Edward Hitchcock, Jr.]], (1828\u20131911) [[Amherst College]] Professor of Hygiene and Physical Education, devoted his academic career to the scientific study of physical exercise, training and the body. Coauthored 1860 text on exercise physiology.<ref>{{cite web |last1=Sweet |first1=William |title=150 Years Ago: Amherst Established Nation\u2019s First College Health Program |url=https://www.amherst.edu/news/news_releases/2011/08/node/337711/ |website=amherst.edu |publisher=Amherst College |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* George Wells Fitz, M.D. (1860\u20131934) Created the first departmental major in Anatomy, Physiology, and Physical Training at Harvard University in 1891.<ref>{{cite book |last1=McArdle |first1=William |last2=Katch |first2=Frank |last3=Katch |first3=Victor |title=Essentials of Exercise Physiology |date=2006 |publisher=Lippincott Williams & Wilkins |location=USA |isbn=0-7817-4991-3 |page=9 |edition=3 |url=https://books.google.com/books?id=L4aZIDbmV3oC&pg=PA8&lpg=PA8&dq=austin+flint+jr+textbook&source=bl&ots=WnqYw7Jg0M&sig=ACfU3U2q1g_HI3hQf9BeuaZogU_Xczp10w&hl=en&sa=X&ved=2ahUKEwjn2q-h4fffAhUrU98KHcEoAPQQ6AEwDHoECAMQAQ#v=onepage&q=austin%20flint%20jr%20textbook&f=false |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[August Krogh]] (1874\u20131949) Won the 1920 Nobel prize in physiology for discovering the mechanism that controlled capillary blood flow in resting or active muscle.<ref>{{cite web|title=August Krogh Biographical |url=https://www.nobelprize.org/prizes/medicine/1920/krogh/biographical/ |website=NobelPrize.org |publisher=The Nobel Prize Organization |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n* [[Per-Olof \u00c5strand]] (1922\u20132015) Professor at the Department of Physiology, [[Karolinska Institute]], Stockholm. Wrote a seminal paper which evaluated the physical working capacity of men and women aged 4\u201333 years.<ref>{{cite book |last1=Astrand |first1=Per-Olof |last2=Rodahl |first2=Kaare |last3=Dahl |first3=Hans |last4=Stromme |first4=Sigmund |title=The Textbook of Work Physiology |date=2003 |publisher=McGraw-Hill |location=USA |isbn=0-7360-0140-9 |pages=260\u2013288 |edition=4th |url=https://books.google.com/books?hl=en&lr=&id=BC9SiAsUPqsC&oi=fnd&pg=PR5&dq=per+olof+astrand+exercise+physiology&ots=8X_O3Zpm0r&sig=EFetDz5pmsfOebJDuu3phsxlXXA#v=onepage&q=age&f=false |accessdate=18 January 2019}}</ref>\n\n== Study of sports science ==\nHigher-education degrees in Sports Science or Human Physiology are also becoming increasingly popular with many universities now offering both undergraduate, postgraduate and distance learning degrees in the discipline. Opportunities for graduates in these fields include employment as a [[Physical Education|Physical Education teacher]], [[Dietician]] or [[Nutritionist]], Performance Analyst, Sports coach, Sports therapist, Fitness center manager, Sports administrator, Strength and Conditioning specialist or retail manager of a Sports store. Graduates may also be well-positioned to undertake further training to become an accredited Physiotherapist, Exercise Physiologist, Research Scientist and Sports Medical Doctor.\n\n== Academic journals in sports science ==\n* ''[[Journal of Applied Biomechanics]]''\n* ''[[International Journal of Computer Science in Sport]]''\n* ''[[Journal of Strength & Conditioning Research]]''\n* ''[[Journal of Swimming Research]]''\n* ''[[Sports (journal)|Sports]]''\n* ''[[Medicine & Science in Sports & Exercise]]''\n\n== See also ==\n* [[Kinesiology]]\n* [[Kinanthropometry]]\n* [[Sports biomechanics]]\n* [[Sports medicine]]\n* [[Computer science in sport]]\n\n== References ==\n{{reflist}}\n\n== External links ==\n* [http://www.bases.org.uk/newsite/home.asp British Association of Sport and Exercise Sciences]\n* [http://www.acsm.org American College of Sports Medicine]\n* [https://web.archive.org/web/20090803130839/http://www.ecss.de/ European College of Sport Science]\n* [http://www.essa.org.au Exercise & Sports Science Australia]\n* [http://www.nsca.com/Home/ National Strength & Conditioning Association]\n\n{{Sport}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n[[Category:Sports science| ]]\n[[Category:Applied sciences]]\n", "name_user": "CricketFanAsia", "label": "safe", "comment": "Sports Science and Medicine is probably a better global term here ....", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Sports_science"}
{"title_page": "Robert L. Barnes", "text_new": "{{BLP sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| name          = Robert L. Barnes\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| office        = Judge of the [[Federal Court of Canada]]\n| termstart     = November 22, 2005\n| termend       = \n| nominator     = \n| appointer     = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| office2       = \n| termstart2    = \n| termend2      = \n| nominator2    = \n| appointer2    = \n| predecessor2  = \n| successor2    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = British Columbia\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| spouse        = \n| alma_mater    =\n| religion      = \n}}\n'''Robert L. Barnes'''  is a judge currently serving on the [[Federal Court of Canada]].<ref>[[Federal Court of Canada]], [http://cas-ncr-nter03.cas-satj.gc.ca/portal/page/portal/fc_cf_en/Bio About the Court]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarnes was born in [[New Westminster, British Columbia]] in 1951.<ref name=\"fct\">{{cite web |title=The Honourable Robert L. Barnes |url=https://www.fct-cf.gc.ca/en/pages/about-the-court/members-of-the-court/judges/the-honourable-robert-l-barnes |website=fct-cf.gc.ca |publisher=Federal Court of Canada |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nHe received degrees from [[Acadia University]] and [[Dalhousie University]] in [[Nova Scotia]].<ref name=\"fct\" />\n\n==Career==\nIn 1978, Barnes was called to the bar in [[British Columbia]] and Novia Scotia, and was appointed to be Queens Counsel in 1995.<ref name=\"fct\" />  Barnes became a Judge of the Federal Court in 2005, and Judge of the Court Martial Appeal Court of Canada in 2006, and a judicial member of the Competition Tribunal in 2015.<ref name=\"fct\" />\n\n==Red Cross==\nBarnes was the vice-president of the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies from 2004-2005 and was president of the Canadian Red Cross Society from 2001\u20132004.<ref name=\"fct\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{FederalCourtsOfCanada}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Robert}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Federal Court of Canada]]\n[[Category:Schulich School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-law-bio-stub}}\n", "text_old": "{{BLP sources|date=November 2019}}\n{{Infobox Judge\n| name          = Robert L. Barnes\n| image         = \n| imagesize     = \n| caption       = \n| office        = Judge of the [[Federal Court of Canada]]\n| termstart     = November 22, 2005\n| termend       = \n| nominator     = \n| appointer     = \n| predecessor   = \n| successor     = \n| office2       = \n| termstart2    = \n| termend2      = \n| nominator2    = \n| appointer2    = \n| predecessor2  = \n| successor2    = \n| birth_date    = \n| birth_place   = British Columbia\n| death_date    = \n| death_place   = \n| spouse        = \n| alma_mater    =\n| religion      = \n}}\n'''Robert L. Barnes'''  is a judge currently serving on the [[Federal Court of Canada]].<ref>[[Federal Court of Canada]], [http://cas-ncr-nter03.cas-satj.gc.ca/portal/page/portal/fc_cf_en/Bio About the Court]</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nBarnes was born in [[New Westminster, British Columbia]] in 1951.<ref name=\"fct\">{{cite web |title=The Honourable Robert L. Barnes |url=https://www.fct-cf.gc.ca/en/pages/about-the-court/members-of-the-court/judges/the-honourable-robert-l-barnes |website=fct-cf.gc.ca |publisher=Federal Court of Canada |accessdate=26 November 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Education==\nHe received degrees from [[Acadia University]] and [[Dalhousie University]] in [[Nova Scotia]].<ref name=\"fct\" />\n\n==Career==\nIn 1978, Barnes was called to the bar in [[British Columbia]] and Novia Scotia, and was appointed to be Queens Counsel in 1995.<ref name=\"fct\" />  Barnes became a Judge of the Federal Court in 2005, and Judge of the Court Martial Appeal Court of Canada in 2006, and a judicial member of the Competition Tribunal in 2015.<ref name=\"fct\" />\n\n==Red Cross==\nBarnes was the vice-president of the International Federation of Red Cross and Red Crescent Societies from 2004-2005 and was president of the Canadian Red Cross Society from 2001-2004.<ref name=\"fct\" />\n\n==References==\n{{reflist}}\n\n{{FederalCourtsOfCanada}}\n\n{{authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Barnes, Robert}}\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Judges of the Federal Court of Canada]]\n[[Category:Schulich School of Law alumni]]\n[[Category:Year of birth missing (living people)]]\n\n\n{{Canada-law-bio-stub}}\n", "name_user": "Iridescent", "label": "safe", "comment": "\u2192\u200eRed Cross:Cleanup andtypo fixing,typo(s) fixed: 2001-2004 \u2192 2001\u20132004", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Robert_L._Barnes"}
{"title_page": "Rajeev Alunkal", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=September 2019}}\n{{Use Indian English|date=September 2019}}\n{{Advert|date=July 2019}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name               = Rajeev Alunkal\n| image              = Rajeev Alunkal.jpg\n| birth_name         = \n| birth_date         = {{birth date and age|df=yes|1973|08|17}}\n| birth_place        = [[Alappuzha]], [[Kerala]]\n| occupation         = Poet, Iyricst,\nOrator,social Activist, \nchairman Kumaranashan Smaraka samithi Govt of kerela\n| years_active       = 2001 to Present\n| imagesize          = \n| othername          = \n| Notable Awards:    = Kerela sangetha nadaka acadamy award\nKerela state Award\nKerela film Critcs Award (Two Times)\n}}\n\n'''Rajeev Alunkal''' ([[Malayalam]]: \u0d30\u0d3e\u0d1c\u0d40\u0d35\u0d4d \u0d06\u0d32\u0d41\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d7d) is a poet and lyricist in Malayalam. He has written numerous poems and songs. He is the Chairman of Kumaranashan Smarakam, Pallana Govt. of Kerala.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/music/music-news/rajeev-alunkal-become-chairman-of-kuamranasan-cultural-trust.html \n|title= Chairman of Kumaranashan Cultural Institution, Kerala\n|date= 18 March 2017\n|newspaper=Manorama Online\n}}</ref> Rajeev has penned lyrics for songs in about 125 movies which includes [[Vettom]], [[Mallu Singh]], [[Kanaka Simhasanam|Kanaka Simhaasanam]], [[Oru Marubhoomikkadha]], [[Romans (2013 film)|Romans]], [[Sound Thoma]], [[Chattakkari (2012 film)|Chattakkari]], [[Angry Babies in Love|Angry babies]], [[Aamayum Muyalum]], [[Happy Wedding]], [[Kuttanadan Marpappa]], [[Aanakkallan|Aanakallan]], [[An International Local Story]]. He has received the Kalasree Award for 2012 from [[Kerala Sangeetha Nataka Academy]] for lifetime achievements as lyricist.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://www.thehindu.com/news/cities/Kochi/akademi-awards-announced/article4438256.ece \n|title= Akademi awards announced\n|date= 21 February 2013\n|newspaper=The Hindu\n}}</ref>\n\nDuring the canonisation ceremony of Mother Theresa at the Vatican, Pope Francis released the poetry \"Theresamma\"  written by Rajeev Alunkal and the Indian Pop singer [[Usha Uthup]] rendered her voice for the same. This poem has also been translated in other languages including English, Bengali, Albanian, Latin and Tamil.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url=http://www.manoramaonline.com/music/music-news/rajeev-alunkal-story.html \n|title= Canonisation of Mother Theresa\n|date= 22 August 2016\n|newspaper=Manoramaonline\n}}</ref>\n\n==Life and career==\nRajeev Alunkal was born to Kandanatt S. Madhavan Nair and Karuvally R. Indira at Kadakkarappally Village in the [[Cherthala]] Taluk, [[Alappuzha]] District on 17 August 1973. He lost both his parents and his only brother when he was young. His first poem was published in 1987 at the age of 14 on [[Nair Service Society]] (NSS)\u2019s Service Weekly. That poem has won Mannam Trophy for best upcoming poet. He became a professional Lyricist in 1994 in Drama through Cherthala Shylaja Theatres. \nRajeev Alunkal made his entry into [[Malayalam]] cinema as a lyricist for the hit song 'Thinkal Nilavil' in the film ''[[Hariharanpillai Happiyanu]]''.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url= http://www.hindu.com/mp/2003/11/27/stories/2003112701200400.htm\n|title= Short-lived happiness\n|date= 27 November 2003\n|newspaper= The Hindu\n}}</ref> Since then, he has written lyrics for 250 songs for more than 125 films. Music Legend [[M. K. Arjunan|M.K.Arjun]] Master's Last Film \"Vellaram Kunnile Vellimeenukal\" Song Lyrics Was Written by Rajeev Alunkal <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/music/music-news/2020/04/06/last-song-of-arjunan-master.html|title=\u0d05\u0d35\u0d38\u0d3e\u0d28 \u0d05\u0d7c\u0d1c\u0d41\u0d28 \u0d38\u0d02\u0d17\u0d40\u0d24\u0d02 \u0d30\u0d3e\u0d1c\u0d40\u0d35\u0d4d \u0d06\u0d32\u0d41\u0d19\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d32\u0d3f\u0d28\u0d4d\u0d31\u0d46 \u0d35\u0d30\u0d3f\u0d15\u0d7e\u0d15\u0d4d\u0d15\u0d4d|website=ManoramaOnline|language=ml|access-date=2020-04-06}}</ref>\n\n==Noted Songs==\n\n* 'Thinkal Nilavil' ([[Hariharan Pillai Happy Aanu|Hariharanpilla happiyanu]])\n* Munthiri Vave ([[Hariharan Pillai Happy Aanu|Hariharanpilla happiyanu]])\n* I Love You December ([[Vettam]])\n* Priyathame Shakunthale ([[Kanaka Simhasanam]])\n* Chembavallikalil ([[Oru Marubhoomikkadha|Oru Marubhumikkatha]])\n* Iniyum Kothiyode ([[Bharya Onnu Makkal Moonnu]])\n* Oru Kinginikkattu ([[Mallu Singh|Mallusingh]])\n* Kaakka Malayile ([[Mallu Singh|Mallusingh]])\n* Mezhukuneerthullipol ([[Flat No.4B]])\n* Nilave.. Nilave.. ([[Chattakkari (2012 film)|Chattakkari]])\n* Arthunkale Palliyil ([[Romans (2013 film)]])\n* Ishtamanennadhyam (Album Ishatamanu)\n* Kannnippenne ([[Sound Thoma]])\n* Machan ente maathram alle ([[Nadodimannan]])\n* Mele Chelode ([[Angry Babies in Love]])\n* Karingallikkuyile (She Taxi)\n* Melle nee maayave ([[Happy Wedding]]) \n* Thamarapu Thenkurumbu ([[Kuttanadan Marpappa|Kuttanadan Marpapa]])\n* Vettam Thattum Vattakayal (Aanakallan)\n\n==Famous poems==\n\n*  Ekakikalude geetham\n*  Achanum njaanum\n*  Theresamma\n*  Naaniyamma\n*  Aaro oral\n*  Yudasinu nandi\n*  Kannaki\n*  Verukalude Vedantham\n*  Anaghashayan\n*  Iniyetra naal\n*  Enikkammayilla\n*  Kunnikkuruvinte maruku etc\n\nAs a Music Director, Rajeev Alunkal has composed music for a few albums namely Kanni ''Ayyappan'', ''Sreedharma Shasthavu'' and the songs have been sung by P Jayachandran, Madhu Balakrishnan and Sujatha, \"Kaazhcha\"- a musical venture for eye donation, thrissur pooram theme song 2014, \"Kunjava\"- a 3D animation film for children etc. He also has penned lyrics and composed music for the title song of Asianet channel's mega serial \"4 the people\". His latest music direction was for the album named \"Shakthi Ganapathy\" and the songs have been sung by Vaikom Vijayalakshmi.\n\nRajeev Alunkal received the \"Kavyasree Award\" for the year 2016 from Indo-Malaysian Cultural Forum for his outstanding works for the poems \"Verukalude Vedantham\"<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url= http://www.manoramaonline.com/literature/literaryworld/rajeev-alunkal-bags-kavyasree-award.html\n|title= Kavyasree Award for Rajeev Alunkal\n|date= 18 March 2016\n|newspaper= Manorama Online\n}}</ref>\n\nRajeev Alunkal has been given Sambashivan Memorial Award for his valuable 20 years of poetic contribution to the film, arts & cultural society.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url= http://www.manoramaonline.com/music/music-news/sambasivan-memorial-award-for-rajeev-alunkal.html\n|title= Sambashivan Award for Rajeev Alunkal\n|date= 12 October 2015\n|newspaper= Manorama Online\n}}</ref>\n\nOn 18 June 2018, Rajeev Alunkal received the PN Panicker Memorial Yuva Prathibha Award organized by PN Panicker Foundation for his contribution to the Malayalam literature field for the last 25 years and also for attracting the younger generation to the wide world of reading by giving speeches at various arts and cultural societies across the state.<ref>\n{{cite news\n|url= https://www.manoramaonline.com/music/music-news/2018/06/18/rajeev-alunkal-bags-award.html\n|title= PN Panicker Memorial Yuva Prathibha Award for Rajeev Alunkal\n|date= 18 June 2018\n|newspaper= Manorama Online\n}}</ref>\n\nHe is a notable Malayalam orator too.{{citation needed|date=January 2020}}\n\n==Published Books==\n\n* Nilavilitheyyam- A collection of poems (2008)- Paridhi Publications, [[Thiruvananthapuram]]\n* Ente Priyageethangal - 1001 Selected songs (2009) - H&C Publications, [[Thrissur]]\n* Verukalude Vedantham - A collection of poems (2015) - DC Books, [[Kottayam]]\n\n==Selected filmography==\n*Maradu357 - Directed By  [[Kannan Thamarakkulam]]  - On Pre - Production Works\n*Hai Halo Namaskaram - Hero Is [[Kalidas Jayaram]] .. On Pre - Production Works \n*Vellaaram Kunnile Vellimeenukal - On Pre Production Works <ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.manoramaonline.com/music/music-news/2020/04/06/last-song-of-arjunan-master.html|title=\u0d05\u0d35\u0d38\u0d3e\u0d28 \u0d05\